p442
aVA stricter version of the big O is the little-o. The difference between big O and little-o is that little-o is a strict upper bound. While the big O says that "the requirement may get as worse as this but not more", the little-o says that the "requirement will definitely not get worse than this". As an example, if I say that a program is formula_1, then it means that the time requirement may grow directly with the size of the input, but if I say that a program is formula_17, i.e. little-o of n, then I'm saying that the time requirement will definitely not grow directly in proportion to the size of the input, the growth rate is somewhere less than it. So in a way, formula_17 is better than formula_1, if we're seeking to reduce the time.
